This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for header syntax and interface binding.

## Core concept

Beanstalk separates syntax discovery from provider binding so source is parsed once without pretending imported interfaces already exist.

## Syntax preparation

The compiler records:

- declaration shells
- import shells and aliases
- structural provider references
- conservative local ordering hints
- dormant root metadata
- source `#Import` contract shells

This phase does not open source provider interfaces or type-check executable bodies.

## Interface binding

After providers compile, retained import shells bind to immutable interfaces. Binding produces stable imported identities, canonical type facts and final file-local visibility without reparsing source.

## Three different relationships

- Structural provider references build Stage 0 graphs.
- Imported symbol bindings feed visibility and AST.
- Local declaration-ordering edges feed Stage 3.

Imported declarations never become local declaration graph nodes.

## Rewrite focus

Explain forward declarations, symbol tables, separate compilation and why parsing once reduces both work and semantic drift.

Canonical details live in both architecture authorities.
